	"conclusion": "For OpenAI, the career page partially precedes Glassdoor: 28% of matched jobs (24/87) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 118 days (median: 75 days). An additional 520 jobs (86% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Glassdoor at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of job postings between January 2024 and April 2026 reveals a nuanced relationship between company career pages and Glassdoor. While Glassdoor published a matched job before the career page in a majority of instances (61 out of 87 matched jobs), a striking 520 unique job postings were exclusively observed on career pages, never appearing on Glassdoor during the analysis period. For the 24 instances where career pages *did* precede Glassdoor, they often did so with a substantial lead, demonstrating an average lag of 118 days and a median lag of 75 days. This indicates that while Glassdoor can be quicker for some shared listings, company career pages are a critical source for exclusive roles and frequently provide significantly earlier access when they do publish first.\n\nThe distribution of these lags further underscores the unique advantage of direct career page monitoring. Only a small fraction of \"career page first\" jobs appeared within a short timeframe (3 jobs within 1-3 days, and another 3 within 8-14 days). Instead, the median lag of 75 days and the average of 118 days highlight that early access on career pages is often *substantially* early. For example, positions like \"Software Engineer, Data Infrastructure\" and \"Software Engineer, Real Time\" appeared on career pages 476 and 463 days, respectively, before their Glassdoor debut, with 9 jobs exhibiting lags exceeding 90 days. This pattern suggests career pages are not merely offering a few days' head start, but frequently capturing roles months in advance or even positions that take a very long time to propagate to external platforms.\n\nHowever, these findings must be interpreted with an important caveat regarding data collection frequency. Over the 27-month analysis period, 200 career page snapshots were processed, offering a relatively granular view (approximately one snapshot every four days). In stark contrast, only 6 Glassdoor snapshots were captured. This significant disparity means Glassdoor's job publication timeliness and overall coverage might be understated, as its infrequent sampling could easily miss jobs or record them later than their actual appearance. Despite this limitation, the consistent presence of 520 career page-exclusive jobs and the substantial observed lags for \"career page first\" roles provide clear guidance for job seekers. To maximize opportunities and gain a competitive edge, candidates should prioritize directly monitoring company career pages for the most comprehensive and often earliest access to job openings. This approach not only uncovers exclusive roles but can also provide a head start of weeks or even months for certain positions before they might ever appear on third-party sites.",
